What is an Operating System (OS)?
An Operating System (OS) is software that acts as a bridge between hardware and user/applications.
Examples:
	Linux
	Windows
	macOS

Main Responsibilities of OS:
	Hardware Management
	Memory Management
	Process Management
	Device Management
	File System Handling
	Security & User Management
	Error Handling & Logging

Why Linux Over Windows?
	Cost-Effectiveness
	Free and open-source (no license cost)
	Lower maintenance cost

Performance & Efficiency
	Uses fewer resources (lightweight)
	Works well even on low-end systems
	Highly scalable (from small devices → data centers)

Security & Reliability
	Strong user permission system
	Less vulnerable to viruses
	Frequent updates without reboot


High uptime (can run for years)

Interview Tip:
“Linux is preferred in servers due to stability, security, and cost advantage.”


Key Functions of OS (Important for Interview)
	Memory Management
	Controls RAM usage
	Allocates memory to programs
	Prevents one program from using all memory

Example: Running Chrome + VS Code + Terminal simultaneously
	Process Management
	Handles running programs (processes)
	Creates, schedules, and terminates processes

Example: ps, top commands
	Multitasking
	Run multiple applications at the same time

Example: Watching video + downloading file
	Multi-User Support
	Multiple users can access system securely

Example: root user vs normal user
	Device Management
	Controls hardware like keyboard, disk, network
	Uses drivers

Error Handling & Logging
	Detects errors and logs them

Example:
	/var/log/syslog
	/var/log/messages

Very Brief History of Linux

Created by Linus Torvalds in 1991
Inspired by UNIX
Started as a personal project
Now used in: Servers, Cloud, Android phones, Networking devices

👉 Interview Line:
“Linux is an open-source Unix-like OS kernel developed in 1991.”

Linux Architecture (Simple View)
User
 ↓
Applications (Browser, Tools)
 ↓
Shell (CLI Interface)
 ↓
Kernel (Core of OS)
 ↓
Hardware (CPU, RAM, Disk)

Components:
    Kernel (Heart of Linux)
    Manages CPU, memory, devices

Direct interaction with hardware
  Shell
Command line interface (CLI)
Example: bash

Applications
  User programs (vim, browser, tools)

Linux Directory Structure (Very Important 🔥)
  Linux uses a tree structure starting from / (root)

📁 Important Directories:
Directory	Purpose
/	Root directory
/home	User files
/root	Root user home
/etc	Configuration files
/var	Logs and variable data
/tmp	Temporary files
/bin	Basic commands
/usr	User programs
/opt	Optional software
/dev	Device files
/proc	System/process info
🧠 Easy Trick to Remember:

/etc → settings
/var → logs
/home → users
/bin → commands

